            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "I tried to run a web search but the browsing tool failed. Would you like me to try again? If you want a quick answer now, I can describe the place from my knowledge (I’ll note where verification would help).\n\nQuick summary (from my offline knowledge):\n- This is Centralia, Pennsylvania — famous for an underground coal-seam fire that began in 1962 after a trash burn ignited a seam of coal.  \n- The fire spread through mine tunnels and fractured rock, producing smoke, steam, dangerous gases, and ground instability (sinkholes, subsidence).  \n- Because of the hazard, most of Centralia’s residents were relocated and many buildings demolished; the town became a near-ghost town and a widely noted modern environmental disaster/curiosity.  \n- A section of Pennsylvania Route 61 was closed and bypassed because the ground and roadway were affected; the fire has continued to burn for decades and has been described as potentially lasting many years.  \n- Centralia draws interest from journalists, historians, photographers, and \"dark tourism\" visitors because of the visible smoke, abandoned streets, and its unusual backstory.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Retry the web search now and return citations (recommended if you want exact dates, current population, or recent developments).  \n- Or—if you mean a different place—tell me which place (or upload a photo / give the name) and I’ll search that.",
